{"title_page": "Blue John (album)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album|\n| name       = Blue John\n| type       = Album\n| artist     = [[John Patton (musician)|John Patton]]\n| cover      = Blue John (album).jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1986\n| recorded   = July 11 & August 2, 1963\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Van Gelder Studio]], Englewood Cliffs, NJ\n| genre      = [[Jazz]]\n| length     = 40:21\n| label      = [[Blue Note Records|Blue Note]]<small> BST 84143</small>\n| producer   = [[Alfred Lion]]\n| chronology = [[John Patton (musician)|John Patton]]\n| prev_title = [[Along Came John]]\n| prev_year  = 1963\n| next_title = [[The Way I Feel (John Patton album)|The Way I Feel]]\n| next_year  = 1964\n}}\n\n'''''Blue John''''' is an album by American organist [[John Patton (musician)|John Patton]] recorded in 1963 but not released on the [[Blue Note Records|Blue Note]] label until 1986.<ref name=\"Blue Note discography\">[http://www.jazzdisco.org/blue-note-records/catalog-4100-series/#bst-84143 Blue Note Records discography] accessed November 3, 2010</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nThe [[AllMusic]] review by Steve Huey awarded the album 4\u00bd stars and stated \"While the grooving interplay between Patton, Green, and Dixon is as instinctive as ever, Braith's piercing, honking stabs are what really liven up the proceedings, giving Blue John  a crazed sense of fun that makes it one of Patton's most infectious and enjoyable records\".<ref name=\"Allmusic\">{{allmusic|first=Steve|last=Huey|class=album|id=mw0000200611|title=Big John Patton: ''Blue John'' \u2013 Review|accessdate= April 25, 2020}}</ref>\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = ''[[AllMusic]]''\n| rev1Score = {{rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"Allmusic\"/> \n}}\n\n==Track listing==\n:''All compositions by John Patton except as indicated''\n# \"Hot Sauce\" ([[George Braith]]) - 7:55\n# \"Bermuda Clay House\" (Braith) - 5:55\n# \"Dem Dirty Blues\" ([[Grant Green]]) - 6:15\n# \"Country Girl\" - 6:51\n# \"Nicety\" ([[Ben Dixon (musician)|Ben Dixon]]) - 5:30\n# \"Blue John\" - 7:55\n*Recorded at Rudy Van Gelder Studio, Englewood Cliffs, New Jersey on July 11 (tracks 5 & 6) and August 6 (tracks 1-4), 1963.\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[John Patton (musician)|John Patton]] - [[electronic organ|organ]]\n*[[Tommy Turrentine]] - [[trumpet]] (5, 6)\n*[[George Braith]] - [[soprano saxophone]], [[Stritch (saxophone)|stritch]]\n*[[Grant Green]] - [[guitar]]\n*[[Ben Dixon (musician)|Ben Dixon]] - [[drum kit|drums]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{John Patton (musician)}}\n\n[[Category:Blue Note Records albums]]\n[[Category:John Patton (musician) albums]]\n[[Category:1986 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded at Van Gelder Studio]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Alfred Lion]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album|\n| name       = Blue John\n| type       = Album\n| artist     = [[John Patton (musician)|John Patton]]\n| cover      = Blue John (album).jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 1986\n| recorded   = July 11 & August 2, 1963\n| venue      =\n| studio     = [[Van Gelder Studio]], Englewood Cliffs, NJ\n| genre      = [[Jazz]]\n| length     = 40:21\n| label      = [[Blue Note Records|Blue Note]]<small> BST 84143</small>\n| producer   = [[Alfred Lion]]\n| chronology = [[John Patton (musician)|John Patton]]\n| prev_title = [[Along Came John]]\n| prev_year  = 1963\n| next_title = [[The Way I Feel (John Patton album)|The Way I Feel]]\n| next_year  = 1964\n}}\n\n'''''Blue John''''' is an album by American organist [[John Patton (musician)|John Patton]] recorded in 1963 but not released on the [[Blue Note Records|Blue Note]] label until 1986.<ref name=\"Blue Note discography\">[http://www.jazzdisco.org/blue-note-records/catalog-4100-series/#bst-84143 Blue Note Records discography] accessed November 3, 2010</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nThe [[Allmusic]] review by Steve Huey awarded the album 4\u00bd stars and stated \"While the grooving interplay between Patton, Green, and Dixon is as instinctive as ever, Braith's piercing, honking stabs are what really liven up the proceedings, giving Blue John  a crazed sense of fun that makes it one of Patton's most infectious and enjoyable records\".<ref name=\"Allmusic\">Huey, S. [{{Allmusic|class=album|id=blue-john-r145280|pure_url=yes}} Allmusic Review] accessed November 3, 2010</ref>\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = ''[[Allmusic]]''\n| rev1Score = {{rating|4.5|5}}<ref name=\"Allmusic\"/> \n}}\n\n==Track listing==\n:''All compositions by John Patton except as indicated''\n# \"Hot Sauce\" ([[George Braith]]) - 7:55\n# \"Bermuda Clay House\" (Braith) - 5:55\n# \"Dem Dirty Blues\" ([[Grant Green]]) - 6:15\n# \"Country Girl\" - 6:51\n# \"Nicety\" ([[Ben Dixon (musician)|Ben Dixon]]) - 5:30\n# \"Blue John\" - 7:55\n*Recorded at Rudy Van Gelder Studio, Englewood Cliffs, New Jersey on July 11 (tracks 5 & 6) and August 6 (tracks 1-4), 1963.\n\n==Personnel==\n*[[John Patton (musician)|John Patton]] - [[electronic organ|organ]]\n*[[Tommy Turrentine]] - [[trumpet]] (5, 6)\n*[[George Braith]] - [[soprano saxophone]], [[Stritch (saxophone)|stritch]]\n*[[Grant Green]] - [[guitar]]\n*[[Ben Dixon (musician)|Ben Dixon]] - [[drum kit|drums]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{John Patton (musician)}}\n\n[[Category:Blue Note Records albums]]\n[[Category:John Patton (musician) albums]]\n[[Category:1986 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded at Van Gelder Studio]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Alfred Lion]]\n", "name_user": "Lester Mobley", "label": "safe", "comment": "corrected allmusic reference", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blue_John_(album)"}
{"title_page": "Jen Taylor", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{About|the voice actress|others|Jennifer Taylor (disambiguation){{!}}Jennifer Taylor}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Jen Taylor\n| image              = Jen Taylor.jpg\n| caption            = Jen Taylor in 2007\n| birth_name         = Jennifer Lee Taylor\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1973|2|17}}<ref>{{cite tweet|user=jentaylorfortown | first=Jen | last=Taylor | number= 832737204468211712|title=Thank you for my happy birthday wishes, friends! It has been relaxing and full of cheese which explains this photo. | date=February 17, 2017 | access-date=March 22, 2017 }}</ref>\n| birth_place        = [[Seattle]], Washington, U.S.\n| occupation         = Actress, voice actress\n| alias              = \n| yearsactive        = 1993\u2013present\n}}\n'''Jennifer Lee Taylor''' (born February 17, 1973) is an American actress and voice actress best known for her roles as [[Cortana (Halo)|Cortana]] in various [[Halo (series)|''Halo'' games]] as well as the [[Cortana|intelligent personal assistant]] of the same name. She also voices Zoey in ''[[Left 4 Dead]]''; [[Princess Peach]], [[Toad (Nintendo)|Toad]], and [[Toadette]] in various [[Mario (franchise)|''Mario'' games]] between 1999 and 2008;<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://southtexasgamersexpo.com/jen-taylor/|title=Jen Taylor - South Texas Gamers Expo|date=August 19, 2016|newspaper=South Texas Gamers Expo|language=en-US|access-date=January 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170116170458/http://southtexasgamersexpo.com/jen-taylor/|archive-date=January 16, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> Salem in ''[[RWBY]]'', and Lina, Windranger, Puck and Medusa in ''[[Dota 2]]''.\n\n== Filmography ==\n=== Live action ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|+ List of acting performances in television and film\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\"| Notes\n! 